#    Annotation Properties
#################################################################

dc:creator rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .
dc:subject rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .
skos:example rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .
skos:note rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty .
:legalBasis rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty ;
            rdfs:label "Legal Basis" ;
            rdfs:comment "References to Austrian tax law provisions supporting this definition" .

#################################################################
#    Classes
#################################################################

### Main Entity Types

:TaxableEntity rdf:type owl:Class ;
               rdfs:label "Taxable Entity"@en ;
               rdfs:label "Steuerpflichtiges Subjekt"@de ;
               rdfs:comment """Any natural person, legal person, or other entity that may be subject to Austrian tax obligations.

This includes Austrian residents, non-residents with Austrian-source income, businesses operating in Austria,
and any other entity that may have Austrian tax filing requirements under the Income Tax Act (EStG) or
Corporate Income Tax Act (KStG).

The classification as a taxable entity does not automatically create a filing obligation - this depends on
additional factors such as income thresholds, business activities, and specific legal provisions.

2025 Update: Electronic filing via FinanzOnline is now mandatory unless technical impossibility can be demonstrated."""@en ;
               skos:example "Individual earning salary in Austria, German company with Austrian subsidiary, US investor with Austrian rental income" ;
               :legalBasis "EStG §1 (Tax liability), BAO §6 (Taxpayer definition)" .

:Person rdf:type owl:Class ;
        rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
        rdfs:label "Natural Person"@en ;
        rdfs:label "Natürliche Person"@de ;
        rdfs:comment """An individual human being who may be subject to Austrian income tax (Einkommensteuer).

Natural persons are subject to Austrian income tax if they:
1. Have their domicile (Wohnsitz) or habitual residence (gewöhnlicher Aufenthalt) in Austria (unlimited tax liability)
2. Are non-residents but have Austrian-source income (limited tax liability)
3. Are Austrian citizens living abroad but maintain significant economic ties to Austria

Income tax rates for natural persons range from 0% to 55% (including solidarity tax) depending on income level.

2025 Filing Thresholds:
- €13,308 for income without wage tax liability
- €14,517 for income with wage tax liability plus additional income >€730
- Mandatory filing for self-employed regardless of amount"""@en ;
        skos:example "Austrian employee earning €35,000 annually, German freelancer with Austrian clients, retiree receiving Austrian pension" ;
        :legalBasis "EStG §1 (Income tax liability for natural persons), EStG §33 (Tax rates), EStG §42 (2025 filing thresholds)" .

:Organization rdf:type owl:Class ;
              rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
              rdfs:label "Legal Entity"@en ;
              rdfs:label "Juristische Person"@de ;
              rdfs:comment """A legally recognized entity distinct from natural persons, subject to Austrian corporate taxes.

Organizations include corporations, partnerships, foundations, associations, and other business entities.
They may be subject to:
- Corporate Income Tax (Körperschaftsteuer - KSt) at 25%
- Minimum Tax (Mindeststeuer) of €3,500 for corporations
- Various other taxes depending on business activities

Foreign organizations with Austrian operations or income sources may have limited tax liability.
Account-keeping businesses must submit balance sheets and profit-and-loss statements."""@en ;
              skos:example "Austrian GmbH, German AG with Austrian branch, International foundation with Austrian assets" ;
              :legalBasis "KStG §1 (Corporate tax liability), BAO §26 (Legal persons), EStG §44 (Account-keeping requirements)" .

:SoleTrader rdf:type owl:Class ;
            rdfs:subClassOf :Person ;
            rdfs:label "Sole Trader"@en ;
            rdfs:label "Einzelunternehmer"@de ;
            rdfs:comment """An individual conducting business activities as a sole proprietor.

Sole traders include:
- Traditional business owners
- New self-employed persons (Neue Selbständige)
- Freelancers and independent professionals
- Various service providers

All sole traders must file income tax returns regardless of income level and are subject to:
- Electronic filing requirements via FinanzOnline
- Quarterly advance tax payments if exceeding €3,900 annually
- Proper business record keeping
- VAT registration if turnover exceeds €30,000"""@en ;
            skos:example "Independent consultant, Restaurant owner, Freelance designer, New self-employed IT specialist" ;
            :legalBasis "EStG §22 (Commercial business income), EStG §23 (Independent personal services), EStG §42 (Filing obligation)" .

:Corporation rdf:type owl:Class ;
             rdfs:subClassOf :Organization ;
             rdfs:label "Corporation"@en ;
             rdfs:label "Kapitalgesellschaft"@de ;
             rdfs:comment """A legal entity with separate legal personality, including stock corporations (AG), 
limited liability companies (GmbH), and similar entities.

Austrian corporations are subject to:
- Corporate income tax (KSt) at 25% on worldwide income
- Minimum corporate tax of €3,500 annually
- Group taxation rules for qualifying corporate groups
- Participation exemption for qualifying shareholdings

Filing deadline: Generally within 5 months after fiscal year end, extendable to 9 months with tax advisor representation.
Must submit Form K (corporate income tax return) rather than personal income tax forms."""@en ;
             skos:example "GmbH (Limited Liability Company), AG (Stock Corporation), SE (European Company)" ;
             :legalBasis "KStG §1 (Corporate tax liability), KStG §7 (Tax rates), KStG §10 (Minimum tax)" .

:Partnership rdf:type owl:Class ;
             rdfs:subClassOf :Organization ;
             rdfs:label "Partnership"@en ;
             rdfs:label "Personengesellschaft"@de ;
             rdfs:comment """A business entity where partners share ownership and management responsibilities.

In Austria, partnerships are generally transparent for tax purposes (fiscal transparency principle).
The partnership itself typically doesn't pay income tax, but partners are taxed on their share of profits.

Types include:
- General Partnership (OG - Offene Gesellschaft)
- Limited Partnership (KG - Kommanditgesellschaft)
- Companies constituted under civil law (Gesellschaft bürgerlichen Rechts)
- European Economic Interest Groupings (EEIGs)

Partnerships must file Form E6, and individual partners must file Form E11."""@en ;
             skos:example "OG (General Partnership), KG (Limited Partnership), Law firm partnership, EEIG" ;
             :legalBasis "EStG §23 (Income from partnerships), EStG §188 (Partnership taxation)" .

### Residency Status

:ResidentEntity rdf:type owl:Class ;
                rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
                rdfs:label "Austrian Tax Resident"@en ;
                rdfs:label "Österreichischer Steuerinländer"@de ;
                rdfs:comment """An entity with unlimited tax liability in Austria (unbeschränkte Steuerpflicht).

For natural persons, tax residency is established by:
1. Domicile (Wohnsitz) in Austria - place where person maintains a dwelling with intention to permanently reside
2. Habitual residence (gewöhnlicher Aufenthalt) - staying in Austria for more than 6 months
3. Austrian citizenship with close economic ties (even if residing abroad)

Tax residents are subject to Austrian income tax on their worldwide income, but may claim foreign tax credits
for taxes paid abroad under double taxation treaties.

2025 Filing Requirements apply based on income thresholds and types.
Special rules apply for individuals moving to/from Austria during a tax year (pro-rata taxation)."""@en ;
                skos:example "Austrian citizen living in Vienna, German executive relocated to Austria for work, EU national residing in Austria >6 months" ;
                :legalBasis "EStG §1 (Unlimited tax liability), BAO §26 (Domicile and habitual residence)" .

:NonResidentEntity rdf:type owl:Class ;
                   rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
                   rdfs:label "Non-Resident Entity"@en ;
                   rdfs:label "Beschränkt Steuerpflichtiger"@de ;
                   rdfs:comment """An entity with limited tax liability in Austria (beschränkte Steuerpflicht).

Non-residents are only taxed on specific types of Austrian-source income, including:
- Employment income from Austrian employers
- Business income from permanent establishments in Austria
- Income from Austrian real estate
- Certain investment income from Austrian sources
- Directors' fees from Austrian companies

Tax rates may differ from residents, and double taxation treaty provisions may apply.
Withholding tax often applies to investment income paid to non-residents.
Filing requirements depend on income type and amount, with special rules for EU Member State traders."""@en ;
                   skos:example "German employee working in Austria, Swiss investor in Austrian stocks, Italian company with Austrian branch" ;
                   :legalBasis "EStG §98 (Limited tax liability), Double taxation treaties" ;
                   owl:disjointWith :ResidentEntity .

### Income Types (Seven Categories per EStG §2)

:Income rdf:type owl:Class ;
        rdfs:label "Income"@en ;
        rdfs:label "Einkünfte"@de ;
        rdfs:comment """Revenue or earnings subject to Austrian income tax classification.

Austrian tax law categorizes income into seven specific types (Einkunftsarten) per EStG §2:
1. Agriculture and forestry (Land- und Forstwirtschaft)
2. Commercial business (Gewerbebetrieb) 
3. Independent personal services (selbständige Arbeit)
4. Employment (nichtselbständige Arbeit)
5. Capital assets (Kapitalvermögen)
6. Rental and leasing (Vermietung und Verpachtung)
7. Other income (sonstige Einkünfte)

Each income type has specific calculation rules, deductions, and tax treatment.
The distinction between wage tax liable and non-wage tax liable income is crucial for filing thresholds."""@en ;
        skos:example "Salary, business profits, rental income, investment dividends, freelance fees" ;
        :legalBasis "EStG §2 (Types of income), EStG §§21-29 (Specific income categories)" .

:WageTaxLiableIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                     rdfs:subClassOf :Income ;
                     rdfs:label "Wage Tax Liable Income"@en ;
                     rdfs:label "Lohnsteuerpflichtige Einkünfte"@de ;
                     rdfs:comment """Income subject to wage tax withholding (Lohnsteuer) by the payer.

This primarily includes employment income where employers automatically withhold taxes.
Special 2025 filing rules apply when wage tax liable income is combined with other income:
- Filing required if total income >€14,517 AND additional non-wage income >€730
- Multiple employment situations trigger filing requirements
- Multiple pensions without joint tax deduction require filing

The wage tax withholding system aims to settle tax liability automatically for simple employment cases."""@en ;
                     skos:example "Monthly salary with automatic tax withholding, Director's fees with wage tax deduction" ;
                     :legalBasis "EStG §25 (Employment income), EStG §67 (Wage tax withholding), EStG §42 (2025 filing thresholds)" .

:NonWageTaxLiableIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                        rdfs:subClassOf :Income ;
                        rdfs:label "Non-Wage Tax Liable Income"@en ;
                        rdfs:label "Nicht-lohnsteuerpflichtige Einkünfte"@de ;
                        rdfs:comment """Income not subject to automatic wage tax withholding.

This includes most self-employment income, business profits, rental income, and investment income.
2025 filing threshold: €13,308 for residents with only non-wage tax liable income.

These income types typically require taxpayers to:
- Calculate their own tax liability
- Make quarterly advance payments if exceeding thresholds
- Maintain proper records and documentation
- File annual returns regardless of amount (for self-employed)"""@en ;
                        skos:example "Business profits, rental income, freelance fees, foreign investment income" ;
                        :legalBasis "EStG §22-24, §26-29 (Various non-employment income types), EStG §42 (Filing thresholds)" ;
                        owl:disjointWith :WageTaxLiableIncome .

:EmploymentIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                  rdfs:subClassOf :WageTaxLiableIncome ;
                  rdfs:label "Employment Income"@en ;
                  rdfs:label "Einkünfte aus nichtselbständiger Arbeit"@de ;
                  rdfs:comment """Income from dependent employment relationships, including salaries, wages, bonuses, and benefits.

Key features:
- Subject to payroll tax withholding (Lohnsteuer) by employer
- Automatic deduction of €132 work-related expenses (Werbungskosten) unless higher expenses proven
- Special rules for company cars, stock options, and other benefits-in-kind
- 13th and 14th month payments (holiday and Christmas bonuses) taxed at reduced rates

2025 Filing Requirements:
- Multiple employment situations require filing if total income >€14,517
- Additional income >€730 alongside employment triggers filing requirements
- Foreign employment income may be exempt under double taxation treaties"""@en ;
                  skos:example "Monthly salary, overtime pay, company car benefit, stock options, director's fees" ;
                  :legalBasis "EStG §25 (Employment income), EStG §67 (Payroll tax withholding)" .

:BusinessIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                rdfs:subClassOf :NonWageTaxLiableIncome ;
                rdfs:label "Commercial Business Income"@en ;
                rdfs:label "Einkünfte aus Gewerbebetrieb"@de ;
                rdfs:comment """Profits from commercial business activities requiring regular, independent, and profit-oriented operations.

Characteristics:
- Calculated as business revenues minus deductible expenses
- May require formal bookkeeping depending on size thresholds
- Subject to advance tax payments (Vorauszahlungen) if exceeding €3,900 annually
- Losses can generally be carried forward indefinitely
- Account-keeping businesses must submit balance sheets and P&L statements

2025 Requirements:
- All business income earners must file regardless of amount
- Electronic filing via FinanzOnline mandatory
- Form E1a required for standardized business income/expenditure layout"""@en ;
                skos:example "Retail store profits, manufacturing company earnings, consulting business income" ;
                :legalBasis "EStG §22 (Commercial business income), EStG §4 (Profit calculation), EStG §44 (Account-keeping)" .

:IndependentServicesIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                           rdfs:subClassOf :NonWageTaxLiableIncome ;
                           rdfs:label "Independent Personal Services Income"@en ;
                           rdfs:label "Einkünfte aus selbständiger Arbeit"@de ;
                           rdfs:comment """Income from independent professional services and freelance activities.

This includes:
- Traditional professions (doctors, lawyers, architects, etc.)
- New self-employed persons (Neue Selbständige)
- Freelancers in various fields
- Independent consultants and advisors

Key features:
- No trade tax liability (unlike commercial business income)
- Professional service character rather than commercial trade
- May qualify for simplified taxation schemes
- Mandatory filing regardless of income amount

2025 Updates: Enhanced focus on new self-employed categories and digital service providers."""@en ;
                           skos:example "Medical practice income, Legal services fees, IT consulting, Freelance design work" ;
                           :legalBasis "EStG §22 (Independent services), EStG §18 (Professional services definition)" .

:InvestmentIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                  rdfs:subClassOf :Income ;
                  rdfs:label "Investment Income"@en ;
                  rdfs:label "Einkünfte aus Kapitalvermögen"@de ;
                  rdfs:comment """Returns from capital investments, subject to special tax treatment under the Austrian investment income tax system.

Since 2012, most investment income is subject to final withholding tax (Endbesteuerung):
- 27.5% on dividends, interest, capital gains from securities
- 25% on bank deposits and savings accounts
- No inclusion in progressive income tax calculation (opting for standard assessment possible)

2025 Filing Requirements:
- Foreign capital income subject to 27.5% rate but not covered by Austrian withholding tax (KESt) requires filing
- Special rules for substantial shareholdings (>1% or >€730,000 acquisition cost)
- Form E1kv required for capital income not fully settled by withholding"""@en ;
                  skos:example "Stock dividends, bond interest, capital gains from securities sales, foreign investment income" ;
                  :legalBasis "EStG §27 (Capital income), EStG §95 (Final withholding tax)" .

:RentalIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
              rdfs:subClassOf :NonWageTaxLiableIncome ;
              rdfs:label "Rental and Leasing Income"@en ;
              rdfs:label "Einkünfte aus Vermietung und Verpachtung"@de ;
              rdfs:comment """Income from renting or leasing real estate and movable property.

Key aspects:
- Calculated as rental revenues minus deductible expenses (repairs, management, financing costs)
- Depreciation allowed for buildings and equipment
- Special rules for vacation rentals and short-term lettings
- Foreign rental income included in worldwide income for residents

2025 Special Requirements:
- Private sales of land per Section 30 EStG require filing if no property income tax paid
- Form E1b required for rental income from developed or undeveloped land
- Loss limitation rules may apply for certain types of rental activities"""@en ;
              skos:example "Apartment rental, commercial property leasing, vacation home rental, private land sales" ;
              :legalBasis "EStG §28 (Rental and leasing income), EStG §30 (Private land sales)" .

:AgricultureForestryIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                           rdfs:subClassOf :NonWageTaxLiableIncome ;
                           rdfs:label "Agriculture and Forestry Income"@en ;
                           rdfs:label "Einkünfte aus Land- und Forstwirtschaft"@de ;
                           rdfs:comment """Income from agricultural and forestry operations.

Features:
- Special calculation methods including lump-sum taxation options
- Specific deductions for agricultural expenses and investments
- Environmental and sustainability incentives
- Connection to EU agricultural policy

2025 Requirements:
- Form E1c required for lump-sum income calculation
- Special consideration of EU agricultural subsidies
- Environmental compliance reporting may be required"""@en ;
                           skos:example "Farm operations, Forest management, Agricultural product sales, Livestock breeding" ;
                           :legalBasis "EStG §21 (Agriculture and forestry income)" .

:OtherIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
             rdfs:subClassOf :NonWageTaxLiableIncome ;
             rdfs:label "Other Income"@en ;
             rdfs:label "Sonstige Einkünfte"@de ;
             rdfs:comment """Miscellaneous income that doesn't fit into the other six categories.

This catch-all category includes:
- Occasional services and activities
- Certain types of royalties and licensing income
- Income from temporary activities
- Specific types of gains and benefits

Generally subject to the €730 annual exemption threshold for filing requirements."""@en ;
             skos:example "Occasional consulting, Licensing royalties, Temporary project income" ;
             :legalBasis "EStG §29 (Other income)" .

:AustrianSourceIncome rdf:type owl:Class ;
                      rdfs:subClassOf :Income ;
                      rdfs:label "Austrian Source Income"@en ;
                      rdfs:label "Österreichische Einkünfte"@de ;
                      rdfs:comment """Income that originates from Austrian sources and creates Austrian tax liability for non-residents.

Austrian source income includes:
- Employment services performed in Austria
- Business operations through permanent establishment in Austria
- Real estate located in Austria
- Capital income from Austrian payers (subject to withholding)
- Professional services performed in Austria

Double taxation treaties may modify source rules and provide exemptions or reduced tax rates.
Special rules apply for EU Member State traders operating in Austria."""@en ;
                      skos:example "Salary from Austrian employer, Profits from Austrian branch, Rental from Austrian property" ;
                      :legalBasis "EStG §98 (Austrian source income for non-residents), Double taxation treaties" .

### Filing Obligations

:MandatoryFilingL1 rdf:type owl:Class ;
                   rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
                   rdfs:label "Mandatory Filing L1"@en ;
                   rdfs:label "Veranlagungspflichtig"@de ;
                   rdfs:comment """Entities with mandatory obligation to file an Austrian income tax return.

2025 Filing Requirements - Filing is mandatory for:
- Residents with non-wage income >€13,308
- Residents with wage income plus additional income >€730 and total >€14,517
- Self-employed individuals regardless of income level
- Multiple employment or pension situations with total >€14,517
- Account-keeping businesses regardless of income
- Foreign capital income subject to 27.5% but not KESt
- Private land sales per Section 30 EStG without property tax paid

Filing deadlines:
- Paper form: April 30 of following year
- Electronic (FinanzOnline): June 30 of following year
- Extensions possible with justification

Late filing penalties apply for non-compliance."""@en ;
                   skos:example "Self-employed consultant, High-income employee with rental income, Multiple job holder" ;
                   :legalBasis "EStG §42 (Assessment obligation), BAO §134 (Filing deadlines)" .

:VoluntaryFilingL1 rdf:type owl:Class ;
                   rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
                   rdfs:label "Voluntary Filing L1"@en ;
                   rdfs:label "Antragsveranlagung"@de ;
                   rdfs:comment """Entities who may voluntarily file a tax return even when not required.

Optional filing may be beneficial to:
- Claim refunds of excess withholding tax
- Deduct higher work-related or special expenses
- Utilize loss carryovers from previous years
- Apply for tax credits not automatically granted (Family Bonus Plus, etc.)

2025 Updates:
- Optional returns must be filed within 5 years of the end of the tax year
- Electronic filing preferred but paper forms available
- Once filed, the tax assessment becomes binding
- Entrepreneurs should file even for loss years to establish legal evidence for loss carryforwards"""@en ;
                   skos:example "Employee with high deductible expenses, Investor seeking refund of excess withholding tax, Entrepreneur with business losses" ;
                   :legalBasis "EStG §41 (Voluntary assessment), EStG §124 (Refund claims)" .

:NoFilingRequired rdf:type owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
    rdfs:label "No Filing Required"@en,
               "Keine Veranlagungspflicht"@de ;
    rdfs:comment """Entities with no obligation to file an Austrian income tax return.

2025 No filing required for:
- Residents with only wage income below €14,517 and no additional income >€730
- Residents with non-wage income below €13,308
- Individuals whose tax was fully settled through withholding
- Simple employment cases with proper wage tax withholding
- Non-residents without Austrian source income

These taxpayers may still file voluntarily if beneficial for refunds or deductions."""@en ;
    skos:example "Low-income employee, Simple employment case with proper withholding, Student with minimal income" ;
    legalBasis "EStG §42 (Assessment obligation thresholds)" ;
    owl:disjointWith :MandatoryFilingL1 .

:MandatoryFilingE1 rdf:type owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :TaxableEntity ;
    rdfs:label "Mandatory Filing E1"@en,
               "Veranlagungspflichtig E1"@de ;
    rdfs:comment """Entities with mandatory obligation to file an Austrian income tax return.

2025 Filing Requirements - Filing is mandatory for:
- Residents with non-wage income >€13,308
- Residents with wage income plus additional income >€730 and total >€14,517
- Self-employed individuals regardless of income level
- Multiple employment or pension situations with total >€14,517
- Account-keeping businesses regardless of income
- Foreign capital income subject to 27.5% but not KESt
- Private land sales per Section 30 EStG without property tax paid

Filing deadlines:
- Paper form: April 30 of following year
- Electronic (FinanzOnline): June 30 of following year
- Extensions possible with justification

Late filing penalties apply for non-compliance."""@en ;
    skos:example "Self-employed consultant, High-income employee with rental income, Multiple job holder" ;
    legalBasis "EStG §42 (Assessment obligation), BAO §134 (Filing deadlines)" .

#################################################################
#    Object Properties
#################################################################

:hasIncomeType rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:domain :TaxableEntity ;
               rdfs:range :Income ;
               rdfs:label "has income type"@en ;
               rdfs:label "hat Einkunftsart"@de ;
               rdfs:comment """Associates a taxable entity with the specific types of income they receive.

This property is crucial for determining tax treatment, as different income types have different:
- Calculation methods (net vs. gross income)
- Available deductions and expenses
- Tax rates and withholding requirements
- Filing and reporting obligations
- 2025 thresholds for mandatory filing

Multiple income types may apply to a single entity, which often triggers mandatory filing requirements."""@en ;
               skos:example "Person hasIncomeType EmploymentIncome, Corporation hasIncomeType BusinessIncome" .

#################################################################
#    Data Properties
#################################################################

:hasAnnualIncome rdf:type owl:DatatypeProperty ;
                 rdfs:domain :TaxableEntity ;
                 rdfs:range xsd:decimal ;
                 rdfs:label "has annual income"@en ;
                 rdfs:label "hat Jahreseinkommen"@de ;
                 rdfs:comment """The total annual income amount in EUR for tax assessment purposes.

This represents the taxable income after allowable deductions and exemptions.
For residents, this includes worldwide income; for non-residents, only Austrian source income.

2025 Critical Thresholds:
- €13,308: Filing threshold for non-wage tax liable income
- €14,517: Filing threshold for wage tax liable income with additional income
- €730: Minimum additional income threshold when combined with wage income

The amount determines tax brackets, filing thresholds, and social security obligations."""@en ;
                 skos:note "Amount in EUR, represents taxable income not gross revenue. Key for 2025 filing thresholds." .

:hasWageTaxLiableIncome rdf:type owl:DatatypeProperty ;
                        rdfs:domain :TaxableEntity ;
                        rdfs:range xsd:decimal ;
                        rdfs:label "has wage tax liable income"@en ;
                        rdfs:label "hat lohnsteuerpflichtige Einkünfte"@de ;
                        rdfs:comment """The portion of income subject to wage tax withholding (Lohnsteuer).

This property is crucial for applying 2025 filing thresholds:
- If >€0, the €14,517 threshold applies for filing requirements
- Combined with additional non-wage income >€730 triggers filing obligation
- Multiple wage sources may require filing even if individual amounts are below thresholds

Wage tax liable income primarily consists of employment income with automatic tax withholding."""@en ;
                        skos:note "Amount in EUR. Essential for determining 2025 filing requirements." .

:hasAdditionalIncome rdf:type owl:DatatypeProperty ;
                     rdfs:domain :TaxableEntity ;
                     rdfs:range xsd:decimal ;
                     rdfs:label "has additional income"@en ;
                     rdfs:label "hat zusätzliche Einkünfte"@de ;
                     rdfs:comment """Additional income beyond primary wage tax liable income.

For 2025 filing requirements: If an entity has wage tax liable income AND additional income >€730,
and total income >€14,517, filing becomes mandatory.

Additional income typically includes:
- Self-employment income
- Rental income  
- Investment income not covered by withholding
- Business income
- Other miscellaneous income"""@en ;
                     skos:note "Amount in EUR. Critical €730 threshold for 2025 filing requirements." .

:hasMultipleEmployments rdf:type owl:DatatypeProperty ;
                        rdfs:domain :Person ;
                        rdfs:range xsd:boolean ;
                        rdfs:label "has multiple employments"@en ;
                        rdfs:label "hat mehrere Beschäftigungen"@de ;
                        rdfs:comment """Indicates whether a person has multiple employment relationships simultaneously.

2025 Filing Requirement: Multiple non-self-employed jobs held simultaneously require filing 
if total income exceeds €14,517.

This also applies to multiple pensions that haven't had tax jointly deducted by pension providers.
The complexity of multiple income sources prevents accurate automatic tax withholding."""@en ;
